Moving on From Aesthetics - Let’s Discuss Scale

Harken back to last class. We had this plot:

ggplot(data = CIACountries, aes(x = educ, y = gdp)) +
    geom_point(aes(color = net_users, size = roadways))
## Warning: Removed 66 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

At the bottom of the plot, we have a hard time discerning differences in GDP. There are lots of points stacked on top or near one another.

One option we have is to adjust the scale.

As with many things in R, there is more than one way to accomplish this.

coord_trans

ggplot(data = CIACountries, aes(x = educ, y = gdp)) +
    geom_point(aes(color = net_users, size = roadways)) +
    coord_trans(y = "log10")
## Warning: Removed 66 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

scale_y_continuous

ggplot(data = CIACountries, aes(x = educ, y = gdp)) +
    geom_point(aes(color = net_users, size = roadways)) +
    scale_y_continuous(trans = "log10")
## Warning: Removed 66 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

Side-by-Side

ct <- ggplot(data = CIACountries, aes(x = educ, y = gdp)) +
    geom_point(aes(color = net_users, size = roadways)) +
    coord_trans(y = "log10") + 
    theme(legend.position = "none")

syc <- ggplot(data = CIACountries, aes(x = educ, y = gdp)) +
    geom_point(aes(color = net_users, size = roadways)) +
    scale_y_continuous(trans = "log10") + 
    theme(legend.position = "none")

gridExtra::grid.arrange(ct, syc, nrow = 1)
## Warning: Removed 66 rows containing missing values (geom_point).
## Removed 66 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

I tend to like the plot on the left better because it is more clear that the y axis has been translated to a logarithmic scale.

You are not, however, limited to only tranfering the y axis. There are similar functions to to perform similar operations on different aesthetics:

  • scale_x_continuous()
  • scale_x_discrete()
  • scale_y_discrete()
  • scale_color()
  • etc.
